{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17497030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17497030"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:02:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:02:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1460"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1460"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.01,0.03,0.62,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112335"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1460"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94383"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"9486"},{"type":"tags","id":"11501"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46079"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112335"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-year history of a painless, slow-growing swelling on his left cheek. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He is a non-smoker and drinks about four glasses of wine a week. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a non-tender swelling on the left cheek with no erythema or expressible discharge (Image). The lump appears fixed to the skin but  can be moved from deeper facial structures on palpation. There is no facial asymmetry, and ocular and facial movements are normal. There is no cervical lymphadenopathy and no other abnormal findings on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Parotid adenoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Epidermoid cyst","Lipoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidermoid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E. These cysts typically present as slow-growing, painless, mobile nodules with a central punctum (circle in image below), most often on the face, head, neck, or back. The absence of overlying skin changes, discharge, or signs of infection, as well as the lack of risk factors for malignancy, support this diagnosis. The lesion\u0027s mobility and lack of tethering to deeper structures further support a benign cutaneous cyst.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParotid adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E (pleomorphic adenoma) is the most common benign salivary gland tumour and usually presents as a painless, slow-growing mass in the parotid region, often below the ear and overlying the mandible. However, these tumours are typically deeper and may move with facial muscle contraction or jaw movement. The absence of a mass in the parotid region and the presence of a central punctum make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E often presents as a rapidly growing, erythematous, ulcerated, or crusted nodule, frequently in sun-exposed areas. Risk factors include sun exposure, immunosuppression, and prior radiation. The slow growth, lack of ulceration, and absence of risk factors or lymphadenopathy make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common skin cancer and typically appears as a pearly nodule with telangiectasia or a non-healing ulcer with rolled borders, usually in sun-exposed areas. The lesion described lacks these features and has a central punctum, making basal cell carcinoma less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign tumour of subcutaneous fat, presenting as a soft, mobile, non-tender mass. Lipomas do not have a central punctum and are usually softer and more fluctuant than cysts. The absence of these features and the presence of a central punctum make lipoma less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epidermoid cysts present as slow-growing, painless, mobile nodules with a central punctum, most commonly on the face, head, neck, or back.","Facial nerve paralysis in the context of a painless facial swelling is highly suggestive of a malignant salivary gland tumour.","Pleomorphic adenoma is the most common benign salivary gland tumour, typically presenting as a painless, slow-growing mass in the parotid region."],"references":["Jain S, Hasan S, Vyas N, Shah N, Dalal S. Pleomorphic adenoma of the parotid gland: report of a case with review of literature. Ethiopian journal of health sciences. 2015;25(2):189-194. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4478272/","Bokhari MR, Greene J. Pleomorphic adenoma. In: StatPearls [online]. Treasure Island (FL). 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430829/","Kim KS, Yang HS. Unusual locations of lipoma: differential diagnosis of head and neck mass. Australian family physician. 2014;43(12):867-870. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/3914f7cd-f010-4d99-8657-5bd8e49f9398/Unusual-locations-of-lipoma-differential-diagnosis.aspx","Zito PM, Scharf R. Epidermoid cyst. StatPearls [online]. StatPearls Publishing; 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499974/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94383"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1460"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18588"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22083"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18588"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ae220175-49b8-4499-a1fb-2b5e39412002.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ae220175-49b8-4499-a1fb-2b5e39412002.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":368,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"22083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22083"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fKr8iANdVQ5GUsRvfj324Bsm8PeSqC.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fKr8iANdVQ5GUsRvfj324Bsm8PeSqC.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":368,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94383"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-30T08:40:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-30T08:40:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1460"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112335"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","nam